## Interfaces

An **interface** bundles related signals into a single port, reducing repetitive port lists and keeping signal groupings consistent across the hierarchy.

```systemverilog
interface apb_if (input logic pclk, presetn);
  logic [31:0] paddr, pwdata, prdata;
  logic        psel, penable, pwrite;
  logic        pready, pslverr;
endinterface

module apb_slave (apb_if.slave apb);
  always_ff @(posedge apb.pclk)
    if (apb.psel && apb.penable && !apb.pwrite)
      apb.prdata <= reg_file[apb.paddr[7:2]];
endmodule
```

## Modports

**Modports** define directional views of an interface for each role (master/slave/monitor):

```systemverilog
interface axi_if;
  modport master (output AWVALID, AWADDR, WVALID, WDATA,
                  input  AWREADY, WREADY, BVALID, output BREADY);
  modport slave  (input  AWVALID, AWADDR, WVALID, WDATA,
                  output AWREADY, WREADY, BVALID, input  BREADY);
endinterface
```

## Clocking Blocks

Synchronize testbench drives and samples relative to the clock edge, preventing race conditions between the TB and DUT:

```systemverilog
clocking cb @(posedge clk);
  default input #1 output #1;  // 1ns setup/hold sampling
  input  data_out;
  output data_in;
endclocking
```

> Interfaces + modports are mandatory in professional RTL/TB coding — they cut port-mismatch bugs and make IP reuse trivial.

## UVM Factory

Allows swapping component implementations at runtime without editing the testbench:
```systemverilog
// Override base driver with extended driver
my_driver::type_id::set_type_override(my_dbg_driver::get_type());
```
All UVM objects register with the factory using `` `uvm_component_utils `` or `` `uvm_object_utils `` macros.

## Sequences

A **sequence** generates ordered transactions; a **sequencer** arbitrates and sends them to the driver:
```systemverilog
class my_seq extends uvm_sequence #(my_txn);
  task body();
    repeat(10) begin
      req = my_txn::type_id::create("req");
      start_item(req);
      assert(req.randomize() with { addr inside {[0:255]}; });
      finish_item(req);
    end
  endtask
endclass
```

## Register Abstraction Layer (RAL)

RAL provides a high-level API to access DUT configuration registers:
```systemverilog
// Write to a register
reg_model.ctrl_reg.write(status, 32'hDEAD_BEEF);

// Read and check
reg_model.status_reg.read(status, rdata);
if (rdata != expected) `uvm_error("RAL", "Mismatch")
```
RAL auto-generates bus transactions for any protocol adapter, handles address mapping and mirror values, and supports built-in register tests (reset values, access policies).

> The factory + config_db + RAL triad is what makes UVM environments truly reusable across projects and teams.
